            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "Usually in GUI apps the solution is to use scancodes translated to some default layout (I highly suggest taking “some default layout” from OS, not blindly use `us`). This thing is done by X11 when you use Control mappings (but not for Alt). I also see that fluxbox has this behaviour even when using Alt mappings.\n\nNote: I do not know how they actually implement this. What I know are the following facts:\n1. If I run `xev`, press `Control` and another key (letter) in layout `ru` I get events for pressing `Control` and this key in layout `dvp2` (which is programming dvorak with some modifications), not in `ru`. I also see the same behaviour in konsole (`<C-v><C-u>` shows `^U` in dvp2 just like pressing the same keys emits the same result in layout `ru`).\n2. If I do the same thing with `Alt` I get key in layout `ru`.\n3. Still if I use `ru` layout and press `<A-r>` (this pops yakuake) fluxbox tells yakuake to appear.\n\nConfiguration used for testing (I do not _actually_ use `ru` layout ever):\n\n```\nsetxkbmap -option 'ctrl:nocaps,grp_led:scroll,grp:lwin_switch,grp:rctrl_toggle,compose:rwin' dvp2,ru ; xmodmap ~/.Xmodmap\n```\n\n### .Xmodmap\n\n```\n! ESC\nkeycode 9 = F13\n!add Lock = Caps_Lock\n\n! Control_R\nkeycode 37 = Escape\n\n! 2*Meta_L\nkeycode 148 = Alt_L\n\n! ! Mouse\n! !+\n! keycode 123 = F13\n! !-\n! keycode 122 = F14\n```\n\nThus the suggested solution is to use whatever fluxbox uses in the GUI when in normal, operator-pending and visual modes.\n",
