            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "Langmap uses Greek as an example, so when I type\n\n```\n:set langmap=ηhξjκkλl\n```\n\nI can use the home row with a Greek keyboard. Furthermore, using `ctrl` and the home row works as well, so it appears that `langmap` is working just the way I want it, right? Then I reset my `langmap`\n\n```\n:set langmap=\n```\n\nand the Greek home row was still working with the `ctrl` keys. My uneducated guess would be that `ctrl`\\+ `λ` gets translated to the same control character as `ctrl` + `l`, so it is a lucky coincidence that it works. The same goes for the Cyrillic `л` character.\n\nMaybe Bram only tested the keys that have the same physical position on the keyboard as the Latin alphabet letters, saw that it was working and called it a day. He is from the Netherlands, and a quick Google image search shows that Dutch keyboards only have the 26 Latin characters found on English keyboards as well. A German keyboard has 30 letter characters (three umlauts and the `ß`), Cyrillic alphabets have around 30 letters as well ([depending on the language](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cyrillic_alphabets)) and a Greek keyboard has only 25 letters.\n\nI'd say `langmap` is simply broken in Vim.\n",
